TY  - JOUR
T1  - Asymptotic efficiency in semi-parametric models with censoring
AU  - Chamberlain, Gary
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 32
IS  - 2
SP  - 189
EP  - 218
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(86)90038-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407686900382
AB  - We consider a regression model subject to bivariate censoring in which the errors are independent of the explanatory variables. Our objective is to drop the assumption of bivaraite normality and obtain an information bound on asymptotic efficiency when the error distribution is unrestricted except for smoothness and regularity conditions. This bound has simple form; if there are no exclusion restrictions on the selection equation, then positive information requires a restriction on the regression slope parameters and a continuous distribution for a component of the explanatory variables. We also consider a binary choice model under the weak assumption that the error distribution has zero median conditional on the explanatory variables. Here the semi-parametric information bound is zero. Hence, although a consistent estimator exists, it is not possible to attain covergence at rate 1n.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - A class of partially adaptive one-step m-estimators for the non-linear regression model with dependent observations
AU  - Pötscher, Benedikt M.
AU  - Prucha, Ingmar R.
JO  - Journal of Econometrics
VL  - 32
IS  - 2
SP  - 219
EP  - 251
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/07/01/
SN  - 0304-4076
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-4076(86)90039-4
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304407686900394
AB  - In this paper we consider a class of partially adaptive one-step M-estimators for the non-linear regression model with dependent observations. Those estimators adapt themselves with respect to a measure of the tailthickness of the disturbance distribution (as well as to a measure of the scale). The large-sample behavior of those estimators is examined theoretically for general disturbance distributions and numerically for various specific ones. The estimators considered are motivated by the Student-t maximum-likelihood estimator. Given appropriate specifications of the adaptation parameter the estimators are asymptotically efficient on the family of Student-t distributions including the normal distribution.
ER  - 

